**Reason 1: Reduced Latency**
CDNs store cached copies of the media on edge servers that are geographically closer to the end-users. <marks>1</marks> This reduces the physical distance the data must travel across the backbone of the internet. <marks>1</marks> As a result, the time taken for a video to start playing (latency) is minimized, and the risk of buffering during playback is significantly reduced. <marks>1</marks>

**Reason 2: Load Balancing and Scalability**
By distributing the traffic across hundreds of edge servers, the load is taken off the origin server. <marks>1</marks> This prevents the main server from being overwhelmed or crashing during periods of high demand, such as the release of a popular new series. <marks>1</marks> It also provides redundancy; if one edge server fails, the network automatically routes the user's request to the next nearest available node. <marks>1</marks>

Note: Candidates can also receive marks for:
- Bandwidth cost savings (ISP peering);
- Improved security (CDNs can mitigate Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks);
- Better handling of varied global internet speeds through local caching;

